   <titles>
      <title>Preview: Oriented Volume</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>The central result of this section is the following geometrical interpretation of the determinant operation.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <table align="center"
                   border="3"
                   bordercolor="Maroon"
                   cellpadding="2"
                   cellspacing="2">
               <row>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <strong>Theorem</strong> – Let <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}_1, \dots , \Vect{x}_n</latex>
                           </math> be <math>
                              <latex>n</latex>
                           </math> vectors in <math>
                              <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                           </math>, and write them as column vectors. Then</para.body>
                     </para>
                     <math.display>
                        <latex>\det [ \Vect{x}_1\ \dots\ \Vect{x}_n] = \omega( \Vect{x}_1 , \dots , \Vect{x}_n ) \cdot \Vol( \Vect{x}_1 , \dots , \Vect{x}_n )</latex>
                     </math.display>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </table>
            <para>
               <para.body>In the formula above, <math>
                     <latex>\omega( \Vect{x}_1 , \dots , \Vect{x}_n )</latex>
                  </math> denotes the orientation of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math> represented by the <math>
                     <latex>n</latex>
                  </math>-tuple of vectors <math>
                     <latex>( \Vect{x}_1 , \dots , \Vect{x}_n )</latex>
                  </math>. This is <math>
                     <latex>+1</latex>
                  </math> if the orientation is positive, and it is <math>
                     <latex>-1</latex>
                  </math> if the orientation is negative. Finally, <math>
                     <latex>\Vol( \Vect{x}_1 , \dots , \Vect{x}_n )</latex>
                  </math> denotes the volume of the slanted box in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math> spanned by the vectors <math>
                     <latex>( \Vect{x}_1 , \dots , \Vect{x}_n )</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>Already the following two examples illustrate the simple beauty of this result.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <strong>Example</strong> – the result</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>
					
\aligned
\det
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
4320 &amp; 4310 \\
89 &amp; 87
\end{array}
\right]\ &amp;=\ 
4320\cdot 87\ -\ 4310\cdot 89 \\
	&amp;=\ 375840\ -\ 383590 \\
	&amp;&lt;\ 0
\endaligned

				</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>means</para.body>
            </para>
            <ul>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>The vectors <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x} = (4320,89)</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{y} = (4310,87)</latex>
                        </math> span a parallelogram whose area is <math>
                           <latex>\Abs{375840 - 383590} = 383590 - 375840</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>The pair of vectors <math>
                           <latex>( \Vect{x} , \Vect{y} )</latex>
                        </math> represents the negative or clockwise orientation of the plane.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
            </ul>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <strong>Example</strong> – the result</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>
					
\aligned
\det
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
3 &amp; 7 &amp; -1 \\
-2 &amp; 4 &amp; 3 \\
1 &amp; 0 &amp; 6
\end{array}
\right]\ &amp;=\ 
	72 + 21 - (-4 + (-84)) \\
	&amp;=\ 181 &gt; 0
\endaligned

				</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>means</para.body>
            </para>
            <ul>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>The vectors <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x} = (3,-2,1)</latex>
                        </math>, <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{y} = (7,4,0)</latex>
                        </math>, <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{z} = (-1,3,6)</latex>
                        </math> span a slanted box in <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                        </math> whose volume is <math>
                           <latex>181</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>The ordered triple of vectors <math>
                           <latex>( \Vect{x} , \Vect{y} , \Vect{z} )</latex>
                        </math> represents the positive or right hand orientation of the <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
            </ul>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </body>
